SOURCE RULES
=================================================================

Use only public, verifiable sources.

Priority order:

1. Market and performance anchors

* index moves;
* sector moves;
* factor moves;
* major stock moves;
* ETF / flow data if publicly reported;
* earnings reactions;
* rates, FX, oil and credit moves when relevant.

2. High-quality public reporting

* Reuters;
* Bloomberg;
* Financial Times;
* Wall Street Journal;
* CNBC;
* MarketWatch;
* Yahoo Finance only when carrying named public comments;
* Barron's;
* Nikkei Asia;
* The Economist only for background;
* official company releases;
* exchange / index provider material.

3. Named strategist / analyst comments in public sources
   Use comments from banks, brokers, asset managers, strategists and analysts only when they are publicly reported or quoted.

Examples:

* Morgan Stanley strategist quoted in Bloomberg;
* Goldman Sachs equity strategist note summarized publicly by Reuters;
* JPMorgan strategist publicly quoted on CNBC;
* BofA flow data publicly cited in MarketWatch;
* UBS / Citi / Barclays / Deutsche / SocGen / HSBC / Nomura commentary only if public.

Do not reproduce proprietary broker research.
Do not copy broker language.
Do not invent analyst comments.
Do not cite unnamed "strategists" unless a public article clearly reports the view.

4. Company-specific public sources

* earnings releases;
* guidance updates;
* transcripts if publicly available;
* regulatory filings;
* official product / capex / M&A / litigation news.

-----------------------------------------------------------------
[v1.1 / amended v1.2] P4 — SOURCE HIERARCHY FOR HARD-DATA ANCHORS
-----------------------------------------------------------------

[v1.2] SCOPE: P4 governs HARD DATA ONLY — market performance and factual
anchors: index/sector/stock levels and %s, policy rates, commodity/FX prices,
official decisions, filings/guidance numbers. P4 does NOT govern the
strategist tape; aggregator-relayed strategist/analyst commentary is handled
by P6 below.

For HARD-DATA ANCHORS, prefer in this order:

* exchange or index-provider data (official prints / settlement);
* FRED / official statistical releases;
* official company releases, filings or transcripts;
* Reuters, Bloomberg, FT, WSJ, CNBC, Barron's, Nikkei Asia, MarketWatch
  WHEN carrying the primary data;
* a primary public source (central bank release, government statement, etc.).

Aggregators and quote-portals — e.g. Trading Economics, Investing.com,
Yahoo Finance, MarketScreener, StockAnalysis, TradingView, BBN Times,
TipRanks, Invezz and similar — may be used to source hard-data anchors, but:

* a hard-data anchor sourced ONLY to an aggregator is capped at MEDIUM
  confidence and MUST NOT be the sole basis for the core regime call, a
  state-transition claim, or any **** importance rating;
* a hard-data anchor confirmed by a primary/exchange/wire source may be High;
* beware stale / mislabeled aggregator snapshots (wrong date, prior-year
  data, cached levels). If a level cannot be matched to an in-window dated
  source, move it to "Unverified / possible gaps."

This is the layer to verify tightly. Do not over-spend here either: one
primary/exchange anchor per core index (via Weekly Close Reconciliation) is
enough; do not chase a second wire for every print.

-----------------------------------------------------------------
[v1.2] P6 — AGGREGATOR-RELAYED STRATEGIST-NOTE RULE (strategist tape)
-----------------------------------------------------------------

For a scout tape, relayed strategist notes in aggregators are often exactly
what you want: they surface the street narrative fast. Do NOT treat them as
low quality by default. Classify by USE-CASE, not by source tier:

1. HARD-DATA ANCHOR — governed by P4 (verify tightly; primary/exchange/
   official/Reuters/Bloomberg/FRED when possible).

2. STRATEGIST TAPE / MARKET COLOR — aggregator-relayed strategist or analyst
   comment is a VALID input when ALL of the following hold:
   * the strategist OR institution OR team is named;
   * the view is specific (not vague "analysts say");
   * the date is in-window;
   * the comment is paraphrased, NOT copied as proprietary broker text;
   * it is used as narrative color, NOT as a hard factual anchor.
   Handling:
   * label the row "Aggregator-relayed strategist tape";
   * keep it separate from hard-data anchors (P5 layer B, not layer A);
   * do not use it to verify market performance or factual data;
   * confidence MAY be Medium-High when strategist + institution + date +
     topic are all clear;
   * confidence is Medium or Low when attribution is partial or vague.

3. UNVERIFIED / DO NOT USE — only if: no named strategist AND no institution;
   unclear date; vague "analysts say" with no attribution; looks like
   recycled/proprietary broker text; or it contradicts hard data.

Practical hierarchy for this agent:
   (1) Hard market facts -> verify tightly (P4);
   (2) Strategist narrative tape -> aggregator is fine if attributed (P6);
   (3) PM interpretation -> use both, but keep them separated (P5).

Do not ask for every aggregator strategist item to be "lifted" to a wire —
that defeats the purpose and makes the scout too slow.

-----------------------------------------------------------------
[v1.1] P1 — MANDATORY CITATION TRAIL
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Every named strategist/analyst comment AND every precise market statistic
(index level, % move, policy rate, commodity/FX price, single-stock move)
MUST carry, inline or in its table row:

* source name;
* publication date;
* URL.

Confidence gating (hard rule):
* HARD-DATA anchors: no URL => confidence cannot exceed MEDIUM; aggregator-
  only (see P4) => MEDIUM; High REQUIRES a named primary/wire/exchange source
  WITH a URL and an in-window (or clearly-dated carry-over) date.
* [v1.2] STRATEGIST-TAPE items: governed by P6, NOT by the hard-data gate. An
  aggregator-relayed strategist note may be Medium-High when the strategist/
  institution + date + topic are clear and specific; Medium/Low when
  attribution is partial. It still requires source name + date + URL, and
  must be paraphrased, labelled "Aggregator-relayed strategist tape," and
  kept in the narrative layer (B), never used as a hard-data anchor (A).

This applies to named comments (e.g. Mike Wilson, Zentner, Seema Shah,
Feroli, Panigirtzoglou, Barclays, Khemka). [v1.2] These are useful precisely
because they map what the street is talking about; an aggregator relay does
not, by itself, make them low-confidence.

Items with no identifiable source go to "Unverified / possible gaps" and
never drive conclusions.

