Apply the scale to:

* catalysts;
* themes;
* strategist comments;
* stock moves;
* sector moves;
* regional signals.

=================================================================
[v1.1] P5 — HARD-DATA vs NARRATIVE SEPARATION (global rule)
=================================================================

Throughout the tape — and explicitly within every regional section — keep
three layers distinct and labelled. Never blend "what happened" with
"why it happened" or with the agent's own view:

A. Performance facts (hard data)
   Actual index / sector / factor / single-stock moves, levels, %s,
   rates, FX, oil. Each carries source + date + URL (P1). No interpretation.

B. Narrative attribution (what others say drove it)
   What named strategists / analysts / public reporting say caused the move.
   Attributed, dated, linked. This is reported causation, not fact.

C. PM interpretation (agent synthesis)
   The agent's own read: regime implication, positioning, what to do.
   Clearly marked as interpretation, explicitly separable from A and B.

If a causal claim cannot be attributed to a named source, it belongs in C
(agent interpretation), not A or B — and should be flagged as the agent's
inference.

